arser path. Cursor's normal chat\n303\thistory is local SQLite, and its documented portable flow is Markdown export.\n304\tThat deserves a separate design pass later.\n305\t\n306\t## Validation Habit\n307\t\n308\tBefore and after cleanup, run the narrow checks:\n309\t\n310\t```text\n311\tcargo fmt --check\n312\tcargo test -p but-agentlog\n313\tcargo check -p but --features agentlog\n314\tcargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\n315\tcargo machete\n316\t```\n317\t\n318\tFor behavior-neutral cleanup, the best result is boring: smaller code, clearer\n319\tnames, and the same tests passing.\n320\t","tool_name":"Read","tool_input":null,"source_record":{"parentUuid":"[REDACTED:entropy]","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"[REDACTED:entropy]","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","type":"tool_result"}]},"uuid":"[REDACTED:entropy]","timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:33:37.308Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"[REDACTED:entropy]","content":"# Agentlog Maintainability Playbook\n\nThis note preserves the review approach for keeping `crates/but-agentlog`\nsmall, maintainable, and intentionally authored. It is not a second spec. The\nimplementation contract still wins for behavior.\n\n## Source Material\n\nUseful references behind this playbook:\n\n- [Google Engineering Practices: What to look for in a code review](https://google.github.io/eng-practices/review/reviewer/looking-for.html)\n- [Rust API Guidelines checklist](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/checklist.html)\n- [GitHub: Review AI-generated code](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/tutorials/review-ai-generated-code)\n- [Martin Fowler: Code Smell](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CodeSmell.html)\n- [Refactoring Guru: Speculative Generality](https://refactoring.guru/smells/speculative-generality)\n- [Claude Code best practices](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/best-practices)\n- [Simon Willison: First run the tests](https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/first-run-the-tests/)\n\n## What We Are Optimizing For\n\nThe POC should feel like a careful GitButler crate, not generated scaffolding.\nThat means:\n\n- The code solves the problem we know exists now.\n- Names are domain-specific and boring.\n- Types carry meaning, but do not predict future product shape.\n- Boundaries are obvious from reading the module names.\n- Tests encode behavior and intent, not incidental implementation details.\n- Comments explain rationale, privacy, or tricky failure modes. They do not\n  narrate the next line.\n\n## Review Passes\n\nRun these as separate passes. Preserve behavior unless a specific bug is found.\n\n### 1. Deletion Pass\n\nLook for speculative generality:\n\n- one-use traits\n- one-use structs\n- generic helpers with only one real caller\n- parameters added for imagined future agents\n- fields that are always `None` or always the same value\n- comments that repeat the code\n\nDelete or inline when the call site becomes clearer.\n\n### 2. Domain Naming Pass\n\nRename vague concepts to the agentlog/session domain.\n\nPrefer:\n\n- `ParsedRecord`\n- `TranscriptRecord`\n- `session_key`\n- `source_record_hash`\n- `write_session_update`\n\nAvoid names that sound framework-like:\n\n- `Manager`\n- `Processor`\n- `Handler`\n- `Adapter`\n- `Service`\n- `Provider`\n\nOnly use a generic name when there is a real shared concept in Codex and Claude.\n\n### 3. Boundary Pass\n\nThe intended shape is:\n\n```text\ncli -> capture -> transcript parser -> gitmeta writer\n                         |\n                         v\n                    redaction\n```\n\nCheck that:\n\n- CLI parsing and output stay in `cli.rs`.\n- Repository resolution happens before business logic.\n- Transcript parsing does not know GitMeta.\n- GitMeta writing does not know provider-specific transcript vocabulary.\n- Redaction only owns redaction.\n- `but` CLI code remains a small feature-gated bridge.\n\n### 4. Execution Trace Pass\n\nFollow one real command invocation from the `but` entry point down to the\nGitMeta write. This catches ownership and ordering issues that static smell\npasses miss.\n\nFor the capture command, trace:\n\n```text\nbut -> args -> but_agentlog::run_from_dir -> record_transcript -> transcript -> gitmeta\n                                                         -> optional association\n```\n\nAt each boundary, write down:\n\n- which inputs are validated there\n- which paths are made absolute or canonical there\n- which state is discovered there\n- which values are converted to lossy strings there\n- which side effects can happen there\n\nLook for:\n\n- the same input being normalized or rediscovered in two places\n- expensive or side-effecting work before cheap local validation\n- side effects before all relevant input validation\n- two stored facts trying to describe the same source of truth\n- path or repo semantics changing between layers\n- errors whose order no longer matches the user's invocation\n\nFix only local issues discovered by the trace. If the fix requires moving large\nchunks of startup, command dispatch, or persistence shape, document it instead\nof folding it into a cleanup pass.\n\n### 5. Rust API Pass\n\nUse Rust API Guidelines as a checklist, scaled down for a private POC crate:\n\n- Keep items private by default.\n- Public crate surface should be only what `but` needs.\n- Prefer `pub(crate)` over `pub` when cross-module access is needed.\n- Use `anyhow` for this monorepo-only CLI-owned crate.\n- Add typed errors only when callers need to classify failures.\n- Prefer `&str` and `&Path` parameters when ownership is not needed.\n- Avoid clones inside loops unless ownership is genuinely required.\n- Derive `Debug` where it helps tests and diagnostics.\n\n### 6. Test Intent Pass\n\nTests should answer: \"What behavior would break if a maintainer changed this?\"\n\nHigh-value tests for this crate:\n\n- malformed final JSONL line is skipped\n- malformed middle JSONL line fails\n- empty lines do not affect record indexes\n- repeated capture is idempotent\n- growing transcripts append only new records\n- Codex and Claude field extraction preserve the shared transcript record shape\n- redaction catches plausible secrets without schema-specific allowlists\n\nAvoid tests that only restate local implementation structure.\n\n### 7. AI-Specific Review Pass\n\nAsk reviewers or subagents narrow questions:\n\n- What looks over-generalized for a two-agent POC?\n- What would a maintainer misunderstand six months from now?\n- Which name hides a concrete domain concept?\n- Which test would still pass if the behavior were subtly wrong?\n- Which dependency, helper, or module exists only because generated code tends\n  to over-structure things?\n\nDo not ask for a broad rewrite. The output should be small findings, not a new\narchitecture.\n\n## Cleanup Recipe\n\nUse this procedure when doing a maintainability cleanup pass on\n`crates/but-agentlog`.\n\n### Step 0. Establish The Baseline\n\nRun the narrow checks before changing code:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p but-agentlog\ncargo check -p but --features agentlog\ncargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\n```\n\nIf the baseline is already broken, fix or document that separately before\nstarting cleanup. A cleanup pass should not hide pre-existing failures.\n\n### Step 1. Main Agent Reads The Code\n\nThe main agent should read the crate itself first:\n\n- `src/lib.rs`\n- `src/cli.rs`\n- `src/capture.rs`\n- `src/transcript.rs`\n- `src/gitmeta.rs`\n- `src/redaction.rs`\n- nearby tests\n\nThen follow one concrete command invocation from `but` into the crate. Keep this\nas a short call-chain note, not a design document.\n\nDo not spawn subagents yet. The main agent needs enough context to judge whether\nsubagent feedback is useful or just generic.\n\n### Step 2. Spawn Focused Review Subagents\n\nUse subagents for independent review, not implementation, at this stage. Give\neach subagent a narrow lens and ask for findings only.\n\nRecommended subagents:\n\n- **Deletion reviewer**: find fake extensibility, one-use helpers, dead fields,\n  ceremonial modules, and comments that repeat code.\n- **Boundary reviewer**: check that CLI, capture orchestration, transcript\n  parsing, GitMeta writing, and redaction stay separated.\n- **Execution reviewer**: follow `but agentlog capture` from CLI entry through\n  GitMeta write and report duplicated normalization, surprising validation\n  order, or side effects before validation.\n- **Rust reviewer**: check visibility, error boundaries, ownership/cloning,\n  naming, and idiomatic Rust.\n- **Test reviewer**: check whether tests protect behavior and whether any tests\n  are brittle implementation mirrors.\n\nOptional subagents:\n\n- **Security/privacy reviewer**, when redaction or transcript storage changed.\n- **Performance reviewer**, when parsing, redaction, or GitMeta read/write loops\n  changed.\n\nDo not ask subagents to rewrite files. Their output should be a short list of\nhigh-signal findings with file/line references when possible.\n\n### Step 3. Triage Findings\n\nThe main agent should merge subagent feedback into three buckets:\n\n- **Fix now**: behavior risk, privacy risk, confusing boundary, or easy\n  simplification.\n- **Document only**: useful future concern but not POC-sized.\n- **Ignore**: speculative architecture, taste-only renames, or changes that make\n  the POC larger.\n\nPrefer deleting or renaming over introducing new abstractions. If a finding\nrequires a new framework, it is probably not a cleanup finding.\n\n### Step 4. Make Small Behavior-Preserving Edits\n\nEdit in small groups:\n\n1. deletion/inlining\n2. naming\n3. visibility tightening\n4. comment cleanup\n5. test cleanup\n\nRun `cargo fmt` after edits. Avoid mixing a behavior fix with broad cleanup\nunless the behavior fix is tiny and directly discovered by the cleanup.\n\n### Step 5. Run Verification\n\nRun:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p but-agentlog\ncargo check -p but --features agentlog\ncargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\ncargo machete\n```\n\nIf dependencies did not change, `cargo machete` is still cheap and catches\ncleanup leftovers.\n\n### Step 6. Optional Second Review\n\nAfter edits, spawn one or two fresh subagents only if the diff is non-trivial.\n\nGood second-pass prompts:\n\n- \"Review only the cleanup diff. Did behavior accidentally change?\"\n- \"Look for new complexity introduced by the cleanup.\"\n- \"Check whether any tests became weaker or more implementation-coupled.\"\n\nAvoid repeating the full four-subagent review unless the cleanup touched many\nmodules. Re-review has diminishing returns.\n\n### Step 7. Summarize The Result\n\nThe final summary should say:\n\n- what was removed or clarified\n- whether behavior changed\n- what validation ran\n- any remaining deliberate POC tradeoffs\n\nDo not claim the crate is now \"future-proof.\" The point is that it is easier to\nchange later because it is smaller and clearer now.\n\n## Cursor Note\n\nDo not force Cursor into the current JSONL parser path. Cursor's normal chat\nhistory is local SQLite, and its documented portable flow is Markdown export.\nThat deserves a separate design pass later.\n\n## Validation Habit\n\nBefore and after cleanup, run the narrow checks:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p but-agentlog\ncargo check -p but --features agentlog\ncargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\ncargo machete\n```\n\nFor behavior-neutral cleanup, the best result is boring: smaller code, clearer\nnames, and the same tests passing.\n","numLines":320,"startLine":1,"totalLines":320}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"[REDACTED:entropy]","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-desktop","cwd":"[REDACTED:entropy]","sessionId":"[REDACTED:entropy]","version":"2.1.142","gitBranch":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}